  \"##########################\")
```

Long staircase. Practice.

## Loading a level

```scheme
(define levels
  (list level-1 level-2 level-3 level-4 level-5
        level-6 level-7 level-8 level-9 level-10))

(define (load-level n)
  (parse-level (list-ref levels (- n 1))))
```

Play level 1: `(load-level 1)`. Play them in sequence in your
cabinet's game-play-tick.

## Level design principles

- Level 1 introduces the character; teach the primary control.
- Level 2 introduces the primary challenge (gap, enemy, etc).
- Levels 3-6 add one thing each: enemy, pickup, height, hazard.
- Level 7 combines two prior lessons.
- Level 8 introduces a new challenge type.
- Levels 9-10 test synthesis under time pressure.

Ten levels is a pattern-language: introduce, deepen, combine,
challenge. If your game has 40 levels, group into blocks of 10
each; each block starts fresh with a new mechanic.

## Playtest each level

Time yourself. Level 1 should be < 10 seconds. Level 10 should be
30-60 seconds. If any level takes > 2 minutes on first play, it's
too hard for its position in the sequence.

## Sharing levels

Levels are strings. Kids can text each other levels. Print, save,
paste. That's the whole distribution mechanism — no server needed.

Format lets kids read AND write. Kids invent levels by drawing
patterns; they don't need level-editor UI.

## The kid-level test

Give a level to a child. Ask them to read it aloud. If they can
say 'ground, gap, ground, spring, ground, goal,' the format works.
If they say 'a bunch of pound signs,' it doesn't.

Chapter 8's parser + these ten samples = a full weekend of play.")
